<xs:schema targetNamespace="http://fsb.belgium.be/mappingServices/data/country/v1_00" elementFormDefault="qualified" attributeFormDefault="unqualified" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:cou="http://fsb.belgium.be/mappingServices/data/country/v1_00" xmlns:sim="http://fsb.belgium.be/mappingServices/data/simple/v1_00"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">Schema version: 1.0 Date: 2011-02-07 Author: Ignaz Wanders
Definition of geographical regions. Regions are termed countries for the sake of understanding, but it must be kept in mind that a region does not necessarily correspond to the political boundaries that define the everyday use of the term country.
Note that the ISO-3166 codes are also based on "geographical regions of special interest," and not on political boundaries.</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:import namespace="http://fsb.belgium.be/mappingServices/data/simple/v1_00" schemaLocation="simpleTypes.xsd"/> <xs:complexType name="IsoType"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">The ISO type of a country consists of one or more names, as well as codes in different formats.
Currently, the ISO country names are published in English and French only.</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:sequence> <xs:element name="name" type="sim:NameType" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> <xs:element name="iso-alpha2" type="cou:ISO_3166-1_Alpha2Type" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> <xs:element name="iso-alpha3" type="cou:ISO_3166-1_Alpha3Type" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> <xs:element name="iso-numeric3" type="cou:ISO_3166-1_Numeric3Type" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> </xs:sequence> </xs:complexType> <xs:complexType name="NisType"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">The NIS type of a country consists of one or more names, as well as a code in three digits.</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:sequence> <xs:element name="name" type="sim:NameType" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> <xs:element name="nis-numeric3" type="cou:NIS_Numeric3Type" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> </xs:sequence> </xs:complexType> <xs:complexType name="ISO_3166-1_Alpha2Type"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">ISO country codes in the ISO 3166-1 two-letter format. For a complete list, see http://www.iso.org/iso/en/prods-services/iso3166ma/02iso-3166-code-lists/index.html
Validation rules: - two to four upper case letters
Regular expression: [A-Z]{2}
Examples: BE, NL, FR, DE, GB, ES, ... (Note that UK is not a valid country code!)</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:simpleContent> <xs:restriction base="sim:CodeValueType"> <xs:pattern value="[A-Z]{2}"/> </xs:restriction> </xs:simpleContent> </xs:complexType> <xs:complexType name="ISO_3166-1_Alpha3Type"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">ISO country codes in the ISO 3166-1 three-letter format. For a complete list, see http://www.iso.org/iso/en/prods-services/iso3166ma/02iso-3166-code-lists/index.html
Validation rules: - two to four upper case letters
Regular expression: [A-Z]{3}
Examples: BEL, NLD, FRA, DEU, ...</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:simpleContent> <xs:restriction base="sim:CodeValueType"> <xs:pattern value="[A-Z]{3}"/> </xs:restriction> </xs:simpleContent> </xs:complexType> <xs:complexType name="ISO_3166-1_Numeric3Type"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">ISO country codes in the ISO 3166-1 three-digit format. For a complete list, see http://www.iso.org/iso/en/prods-services/iso3166ma/02iso-3166-code-lists/index.html The ISO standards permit certain two-letter codes to be customized by users.
Historic country codes use the ISO-3166-3 four-letter format. For a list, see http://www.iso.org/iso/country_codes/background_on_iso_3166/iso_3166-3.htm
Validation rules: - two to four upper case letters
Regular expression: [0-9]{3}
Examples: 056, 528, ...</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:simpleContent> <xs:restriction base="sim:CodeValueType"> <xs:pattern value="[0-9]{3}"/> </xs:restriction> </xs:simpleContent> </xs:complexType> <xs:complexType name="NIS_Numeric3Type"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">NIS country codes in the three-digit format.
Validation rules: - three digits
Regular expression: [0-9]{3}
Examples: 150, ...</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:simpleContent> <xs:restriction base="sim:CodeValueType"> <xs:pattern value="[0-9]{3}"/> </xs:restriction> </xs:simpleContent> </xs:complexType> <xs:complexType name="TerritoryType"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation xml:lang="en">A territory is a geographic region of "special interest." It is chosen such that if a region has a code, either ISO or NIS, it is considered a separate territory.
A territory has language-dependent names, an optional ISO code and an optional NIS code.
A territory may exist of subterritories. (For example, there exist ISO codes, other than 3166-1, which are used for regions within regions.)
An identified territory has an optional start date and an optional end date. These are relevant when regions split or merge. If a date is not given, it is undefined but considered in the past for a start date, and in the future for an end date.</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:sequence> <xs:element name="name" type="sim:NameType" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> <xs:element name="iso" type="cou:IsoType" minOccurs="0"/> <xs:element name="nis" type="cou:NisType" minOccurs="0"/> <xs:element name="subTerritory" type="cou:TerritoryType" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> </xs:sequence> <xs:attribute name="startDate" type="xs:date" use="optional"/> <xs:attribute name="endDate" type="xs:date" use="optional"/> </xs:complexType> </xs:schema>

If omitted, the endDate is considered to be undefined, but in the future.</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> </xs:attribute> </xs:extension> </xs:simpleContent> </xs:complexType> <xs:complexType name="CodeValueType"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation>A code value generally has a validity period, plus a status.</xs:documentation> </xs:annotation> <xs:simpleContent> <xs:extension base="sim:StringWithValidityPeriodType"> <xs:attribute name="status" type="xs:string" use="optional"> <xs:annotation> <xs:documentation>The possible status values depend on the type of the code.
